@node "Introduction" "MPFontsę AmigaGuide« Online Documentation - Introduction"
@next "Distribution"
@prev "Main"
   @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

   When I bought my @{fg shine}Amiga«@{fg text} back in the late 1987's, I liked the fact that
the machine came with programs that allowed the user to design his own fonts
for usage by various application software. Those were the days where
@{fg shine}Notepad«@{fg text} and @{fg shine}FEd«@{fg text} were dominant in the area of integration with the system
software (they were used extensivly in the documentation of KickStart 1.2).
@{i}These fonts were OK if they were used for displaying text on-screen, but
their printouts had a lot left to be desired...@{ui}

   In late 1989 the outline font technology was beginning to evolve into
various third party applications, particularily @{i}DTP@{ui} and @{i}word publishing@{ui}
software. They printed quite stunning on all printers - even dot-matrix ones
- but were a bit pricey to obtain since they mostly came from @{fg shine}Appleę
Macintosh«@{fg text}. There was not way you could design such fonts on the @{fg shine}Amiga@{fg text}, thus
the supply of these fonts was limited.

   In 1990 this technology was integrated into @{i}AmigaOS« 2.04@{ui}, so that most
application software could use them together with the ordinary bitmap fonts.
However there was still @{i}the problem of obtaining the fonts, not to mention
that you could still not design them in the Amiga@{ui}.

   After the luck of Greek outlined fonts for the Amiga and considering the
fact that one single outline font file from Macintosh, supporting Greek
characters, would cost me more than @{i}$80@{ui} (those days), I decided to design my
own.

   Since there was no Amiga program to design them, I started the font
sketching on plain canvas, trying to make the fonts as precise as possible
by using the most smoothed curves I could draw. This procedure started in
late 1991.

   On 1992, a new program was bought to the Amiga community: TypeSmith. This
program (which was the evolution of another program called Font Designer)
allowed the creation of outline fonts on the Amiga. I was so excited with
this fact that I ordered the software immediately.

   After getting the grips with the software, I started the process of
converting the fonts from the canvas to the vector format that TypeSmith
understood. @{b}This process took over 2 years@{ub} from 1992 till 1994. During that
time I was using my own fonts for my study and university papers, and after
a major recoding - in order the fonts to be @{b}ELOT 928@{ub} (ISO 1000) compatible -
I was trying to approach people in the Greek Amiga market, in order to sell
them. However this was not an easy task since most people did not understood
that they had to pay for their fonts. That left me a bit bitter, but then I
decided to release the fonts to the public in order to become a standard in
the Amiga.

   After uploading the fonts to various Greek BBS's and with the advert of
@{i}Aminet«@{ui}, I decided to release them there too. So, in @{i}1995@{ui} I uploaded an
almost complete archive of my fonts, in @{i}Adobe Type 1@{ui} and @{i}AGFA Compugraphic
Intellifont@{ui} format. In order for the fonts to be more compatible with the
Amiga applications (since most of them relied in the AmigaOS font engine), I
released them with @{b}standard Adobe Encoding@{ub} and without many hints, for the
Adobe Type 1 and Intellifonts, respectively.

   This archive is an updated version of the originals, but with even @{i}more
hints for both Adobe and Intellifonts.@{ui} Also the Intellifonts are even more
enchanced in order @{i}to appear better on screen@{ui}. I also released a couple of
fonts never unreleased before in the public, plus a couple of symbol fonts
and a font @{b}specifically designed for designers@{ub}.

   @{b}@{i}The fonts (@{ub}except the symbol and the designer's one@{b}) contain both English
and Greek characters, are encoded in the Amiga Latin1 format, contain full
hints and are optimized for better output in both printing and displaying.
This is the reason that the fonts are a bit larger than the previous
versions.@{ub}@{ui}
@endnode

@node "Distribution" "MPFontsę AmigaGuide« Online Documentation - Distribution"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Introduction"
   @{b}@{u}Distribution@{ub}@{uu}

   These fonts are released as @{i}FreeWare@{ui}. This means that anyone is allowed
to use them for their own purposes, provided that:

   1. @{b}The fonts are not used or distributed for commercial purposes.
      This requires a license agreement@{ub}. Please contact @{"me" link "Contacts" 0}.

   2. @{b}They don't sell the fonts. I didn't spend 4 years of my life in
      order to make profit for others.@{ub}

   3. @{b}The fonts are not distributed as a part of a commercial product.
      This requires a license agreement@{ub}. Please contact @{"me" link "Contacts" 0}.

   Permission is given to the following people to include the fonts in their
software products:

   1. @{b}Urban Mueller/Stefan Ossowski@{ub} - for the Aminet CD-ROM's

   2. @{b}Fred Fish@{ub} - for his Fresh/Frozen Fish collections.

   3. @{b}To Cloanto Italia srl@{ub} - for their Personal Paint package.

   As always, enjoy!
@endnode

@node "Installation" "MPFontsę AmigaGuide« Online Documentation - Installation"
@next "Credits"
@prev "Distribution"
   @{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}


   @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}For Adobeę Type« 1 Fonts@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

      Unfortunately there is no standard way of installing these fonts to
the Amiga. The way the fonts are installed is different for each application
that uses them; however, here is a simple way I propose:

      1. @{i}Create a directory inside the FONTS: directory (the Fonts
directory
         on your boot disk) named "@{b}_Bullet_Outlines_PS@{ub}" (without the
         quotes).@{ui}

      2. @{i}Copy the fonts (.pfb) and their metric files (.afm) there.@{ui}

      3. @{i}Add the following lines to your @{b}User-Startup@{ub} file, which resides
         in the S: directory@{ui}


                     @{b}; BEGIN MPFonts
                     Assign AdobePFonts: FONTS:_Bullet_Outlines_PS
                     ; END MPFonts@{ub}

      4. @{i}Save your @{b}User-Startup@{ub} file and restart your computer.@{ui}

   You should now point your application software, when it's looking for
Adobe Type 1 Postscript fonts, to look in the @{b}AdobePFonts:@{ub} assignment. This
way it is ensured that you'll save a lot of space since all Adobe compatible
applications can share the same fonts (instead of each one has it's own set)
and there is a "standard" way the fonts are installed in the system.



   @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}For AGFAę Compugraphic Intellifonts«@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   Simply load the @{i}Intellifont@{ui} (or@{i} Fountain@{ui} if you are using Workbench 2.04)
program which resides in the @{b}System@{ub} directory of your boot disk. Click on
the "@{i}Outline Font Path@{ui}" button (the one next to the string gadget
underneath) and select the directory that contains the Intellifonts. Then
select the fonts you wish to install and press the "@{i}Install Typefaces@{ui}"
button.
@endnode

